{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780925647229,"sessionID":"ses_158903c2bffeCx3bRrBHJwKOQa","part":{"id":"prt_ea770c97b001eCShql6pdFixSG","messageID":"msg_ea770c180001S6lu2NadozweRv","sessionID":"ses_158903c2bffeCx3bRrBHJwKOQa","snapshot":"9e9f5c1e5b0017189579a907c64328b8b0403141","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780925658253,"sessionID":"ses_158903c2bffeCx3bRrBHJwKOQa","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_DkukrwQQNVB7WsoFakP7iI84","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","offset":261,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n261:   MCP->>MCP: redact secrets; compute dedup_key\n262:   MCP->>DB: INSERT memories (trigger writes memories_fts)\n263:   MCP-->>Claude: { id }\n264: \n265:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Mid-session: compaction ---\n266:   Claude->>Pre: spawn(PreCompact)\n267:   Pre->>DB: SELECT all 4 context types for project\n268:   Pre->>Sum: write context-summary.md (~60 lines, fallback)\n269:   Pre-->>Claude: ack\n270:   Claude->>Claude: compact transcript\n271:   Note over Claude: Next assistant turn re-reads context-summary.md if needed\n272: \n273:   Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session end ---\n274:   Claude->>Update: spawn(UpdateContext)\n275:   Update->>DB: INSERT progress; trim oldest > 20; UPDATE last_touched\n276:   Update-->>Claude: ack\n277:   Claude->>Eval: spawn(EvaluateSession)\n278:   Eval->>DB: scan transcript-derived signals; propose / write candidate insights\n279:   Eval-->>Claude: ack\n280:   Claude-->>Dev: clean exit\n281: ```\n282: \n283: **Per-step contracts**\n284: \n285: | Step | Read from | Writes to | Failure mode |\n286: |------|-----------|-----------|--------------|\n287: | SessionStart | DB, registry | registry (auto-register only) | Hook silent-fail → no injection; `/openltm:doctor` detects |\n288: | recall | DB (FTS5 + base) | DB (last_recalled_at, recall_count) | Returns empty array; never throws into Claude |\n289: | learn | — | DB (memories, memories_fts via trigger) | Reject duplicate dedup_key; redact before write |\n290: | PreCompact | DB | context-summary.md | If write fails, post-compact session loses fallback only |\n291: | EvaluateSession | transcript signals, DB | DB (memories) | OQ4 — propose vs. auto-write is open |\n292: | UpdateContext | — | DB (context_items progress) | Trim ensures bounded growth |\n293: \n294: ---\n295: \n296: ## 5. Data Model Overview\n297: \n298: The persistent store is one SQLite file (`openltm.db`) under `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}`.\n299: Schema lives in `src/schema.sql` and is extended idempotently by migrations in\n300: `src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n301: \n302: ### 5.1 Tables\n303: \n304: | Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n305: |-------|---------|-----------|\n306: | `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n307: | `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n308: | `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n309: | `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n310: | `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n311: | `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n312: | `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n313: \n314: ### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n315: \n316: | Column | Purpose |\n317: |--------|---------|\n318: | `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n319: | `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n320: | `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n321: | `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n322: | `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n323: | `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n324: | `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n325: | `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n326: | `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n327: | `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n328: | `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n329: | `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n330: \n331: ### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n332: \n333: | Column | Purpose |\n334: |--------|---------|\n335: | `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n336: | `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n337: | `content` | Free text |\n338: | `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n339: | `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n340: | `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n341: \n342: ### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n343: \n344: - `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n345:   Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n346:   insert/update/delete.\n347: - Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n348:   `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n349: - BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n350:   decay factors before returning top-N.\n351: \n352: ### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n353: \n354: The current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n355: \n356: - **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n357: - **Rule sketch:**\n358:   - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n359:   - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n360:     by a decay factor (< 1).\n361:   - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n362: - **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n363:   (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n364: - **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n365:   and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n366: \n367: ### 5.6 Relationships\n368: \n369: ```mermaid\n370: erDiagram\n371:   memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n372:   tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n373:   memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source/target\"\n374:   memories ||--o| memories : superseded_by\n375:   memories ||--o{ context_items : promoted_from\n376:   memories ||--|| memories_fts : \"FTS5 mirror\"\n377: ```\n378: \n379: ### 5.7 Registry (out-of-DB)\n380: \n381: `~/.claude/projects/registry.json` holds the cwd → project_name map. It is a JSON\n382: file (not a table) for cross-plugin readability and trivial inspection. Concurrent\n383: write safety is **not** guaranteed — a known weakness (§7).\n384: \n385: ---\n386: \n387: ## 6. Architectural Decision Records\n388: \n389: Each ADR is short and load-bearing. Format: Status, Context, Decision, Alternatives,\n390: Consequences. Every ADR includes at least one rejected alternative.\n391: \n392: ---\n393: \n394: ### ADR-001 — SQLite as the storage engine\n395: \n396: **Status:** Accepted. In production since v1.0.\n397: \n398: **Context.** The plugin needs durable, queryable, low-latency storage on the\n399: developer's machine. It must survive Claude Code restarts, plugin upgrades, and\n400: machine sleep. Median write latency target: < 50 ms p95 (PRD §8.4 R3). Median recall\n401: < 200 ms (G2). Zero cloud dependency by default (PRD §7 N1).\n402: \n403: **Decision.** Use SQLite (via `bun:sqlite`) in WAL mode, single file at\n404: `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/openltm.db`. FTS5 virtual table for full-text search.\n405: \n406: **Alternatives considered.**\n407: \n408: - **Postgres / managed DB.** Rejected. Adds an installation dependency, defeats the\n409:   zero-cloud promise, and is overkill for single-user data volumes (~10⁴–10⁶ rows\n410:   realistic ceiling).\n411: - **Flat JSON / Markdown files (the pre-1.0 design).** Rejected. No transactional\n412:   semantics, no FTS, no concurrent reader safety, O(N) scan per recall. The current\n413:   `context-summary.md` is the vestigial fallback; it is a *projection*, not the truth.\n414: - **DuckDB.** Considered. Better analytical perf, but heavier binary, weaker FTS\n415:   story, less Bun-native tooling, and write-heavy workloads (learn + decay updates)\n416:   favour SQLite.\n417: - **LevelDB / RocksDB key-value.** Rejected. No SQL, no FTS5, would need a hand-rolled\n418:   index for every query path.\n419: \n420: **Consequences.**\n421: \n422: - (+) One-file backup story; `cp openltm.db openltm.db.bak` is a complete export.\n423: - (+) FTS5 ships in SQLite — no extra dependency for full-text search.\n424: - (+) `bun:sqlite` is in-process; no IPC overhead per query.\n425: - (–) Single-writer constraint (mitigated by WAL); cross-process locking is the\n426:   developer's responsibility to understand.\n427: - (–) Schema migrations must be hand-coded and idempotent (see `src/shared-db.ts`).\n428:   ADR-004 and §7 weakness W3 expand on this.\n429: - (–) Embedding column as BLOB grows the row size fast; the formatter strips it\n430:   before MCP transmission to avoid 260 KB-per-memory responses.\n431: \n432: ---\n433: \n434: ### ADR-002 — Hook-based lifecycle integration\n435: \n436: **Status:** Accepted.\n437: \n438: **Context.** Claude Code is a black-box harness. The plugin needs to (a) inject\n439: context at session start, (b) survive compaction without state loss, (c) record\n440: progress at session end, and (d) propose learnings post-session. MCP tools cover the\n441: \"on demand\" surface but not \"automatic on lifecycle event\".\n442: \n443: **Decision.** Use Claude Code's hook surface for four lifecycle events:\n444: `SessionStart`, `PreCompact`, `EvaluateSession`, `UpdateContext`. Hooks are\n445: short-lived Bun scripts in `hooks/`. They share the DB connection logic with the MCP\n446: server via `src/shared-db.ts`.\n447: \n448: **Alternatives considered.**\n449: \n450: - **MCP-only.** Rejected. There is no MCP equivalent to \"this is a fresh session,\n451:   inject context now\". Without hooks, the developer would have to manually call\n452:   `context` at every session start — defeats J1 and US-1.\n453: - **Background daemon.** Rejected. Long-lived process management on developer\n454:   machines is fragile (sleep/wake, terminal close). Also conflates \"react to event\"\n455:   with \"serve queries\".\n456: - **Polling cron.** Rejected. Not aligned with session boundaries; can't inject at\n457:   start.\n458: \n459: **Consequences.**\n460: \n461: - (+) Hook semantics align directly with PRD user stories US-1, US-4, US-13, US-17.\n462: - (+) Each hook is independently testable and replaceable.\n463: - (–) Hook failures are silent by default — drove the need for `/openltm:doctor` (US-9).\n464: - (–) Coupling to Claude Code's hook contract; if the harness changes the contract,\n465:   hooks break. Mitigated by the `update-wiring.ts` postinstall script that keeps\n466:   `settings.json` in sync.\n467: - (–) Four hook processes per session add some startup latency; offset by Bun's\n468:   fast cold start (~30 ms typical).\n469: \n470: ---\n471: \n472: ### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n473: \n474: **Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n475: \n476: **Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\n477: memories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\n478: single-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n479: \n480: **Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\n481: returns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n482: `embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\n483: boost, return top-N.\n484: \n485: **Alternatives considered.**\n486: \n487: - **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n488:   (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n489:   (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n490:   keyword-shaped.\n491: - **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary\n492:   dependency or a sidecar process. Single-user scale doesn't justify it.\n493: - **Pure FTS5 (no semantic fallback).** Rejected. FTS5 is brittle for paraphrased\n494:   queries (\"how do we handle async errors\" vs. memory text \"promise rejection\n495:   patterns\"). The fallback is the cheapest hedge.\n496: - **Trigram / fuzzy matching only.** Rejected. Tokenisation-aware ranking (BM25)\n497:   beats raw similarity for natural language.\n498: \n499: **Consequences.**\n500: \n501: - (+) Zero extra dependencies; FTS5 is in SQLite already.\n502: - (+) Determinism — same query, same DB, same ranking.\n503: - (–) Embedding column adds storage cost; the BLOB is stripped from MCP responses\n504:   to avoid bloat.\n505: - (–) \"Semantic fallback\" today uses whatever embedding source is available\n506:   (deterministic local hash or a future tool call) — OQ1 in the PRD remains open.\n507: - (–) Recall ranking is not user-explainable today (G-K is the gap).\n508: \n509: ---\n510: \n511: ### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n512: \n513: **Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n514: \n515: **Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\n516: that low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n517: \n518: **Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n519: `importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n520: \n\n(Showing lines 261-520 of 1075. Use offset=521 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"  MCP->>MCP: redact secrets; compute dedup_key\n  MCP->>DB: INSERT memories (trigger writes memories_fts)\n  MCP-->>Claude: { id }\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Mid-session: compaction ---\n  Claude->>Pre: spawn(PreCompact)\n  Pre->>DB: SELECT all 4 context types for project\n  Pre->>Sum: write context-summary.md (~60 lines, fallback)\n  Pre-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude->>Claude: compact transcript\n  Note over Claude: Next assistant turn re-reads context-summary.md if needed\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session end ---\n  Claude->>Update: spawn(UpdateContext)\n  Update->>DB: INSERT progress; trim oldest > 20; UPDATE last_touched\n  Update-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude->>Eval: spawn(EvaluateSession)\n  Eval->>DB: scan transcript-derived signals; propose / write candidate insights\n  Eval-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude-->>Dev: clean exit","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","text":"  MCP->>MCP: redact secrets; compute dedup_key\n  MCP->>DB: INSERT memories (trigger writes memories_fts)\n  MCP-->>Claude: { id }\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Mid-session: compaction ---\n  Claude->>Pre: spawn(PreCompact)\n  Pre->>DB: SELECT all 4 context types for project\n  Pre->>Sum: write context-summary.md (~60 lines, fallback)\n  Pre-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude->>Claude: compact transcript\n  Note over Claude: Next assistant turn re-reads context-summary.md if needed\n\n  Note over Dev,Sum: --- Session end ---\n  Claude->>Update: spawn(UpdateContext)\n  Update->>DB: INSERT progress; trim oldest > 20; UPDATE last_touched\n  Update-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude->>Eval: spawn(EvaluateSession)\n  Eval->>DB: scan transcript-derived signals; propose / write candidate insights\n  Eval-->>Claude: ack\n  Claude-->>Dev: clean exit\n```\n\n**Per-step contracts**\n\n| Step | Read from | Writes to | Failure mode |\n|------|-----------|-----------|--------------|\n| SessionStart | DB, registry | registry (auto-register only) | Hook silent-fail → no injection; `/openltm:doctor` detects |\n| recall | DB (FTS5 + base) | DB (last_recalled_at, recall_count) | Returns empty array; never throws into Claude |\n| learn | — | DB (memories, memories_fts via trigger) | Reject duplicate dedup_key; redact before write |\n| PreCompact | DB | context-summary.md | If write fails, post-compact session loses fallback only |\n| EvaluateSession | transcript signals, DB | DB (memories) | OQ4 — propose vs. auto-write is open |\n| UpdateContext | — | DB (context_items progress) | Trim ensures bounded growth |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Data Model Overview\n\nThe persistent store is one SQLite file (`openltm.db`) under `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}`.\nSchema lives in `src/schema.sql` and is extended idempotently by migrations in\n`src/shared-db.ts`. WAL mode is enabled for read-during-write concurrency.\n\n### 5.1 Tables\n\n| Table | Purpose | Lifecycle |\n|-------|---------|-----------|\n| `memories` | Long-term, durable insights (decisions, gotchas, patterns, etc.). Global or project-scoped. | Permanent unless soft-deleted via `status` |\n| `context_items` | Short-term, per-project context. The 4 PRD-defined types: goal, decision, progress, gotcha. | Mixed: progress trimmed to last 20; goal replaced; decision/gotcha permanent |\n| `tags` | Tag dictionary (unique names). | Auto-created on use |\n| `memory_tags` | M:N join — memory ↔ tag. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memory_relations` | Knowledge graph edges between memories with typed relationship. | Cascading on memory delete |\n| `memories_fts` | FTS5 virtual table mirroring `memories.content`. | Maintained by triggers (insert/update/delete) |\n| `settings` | Key-value config for janitor / provider settings. | Manual or migration-managed |\n\n### 5.2 `memories` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `id` | Primary key, surrogate `INTEGER` |\n| `content` | The memory text. Subject to redaction on write. |\n| `category` | One of: `preference`, `architecture`, `gotcha`, `pattern`, `workflow`, `constraint` |\n| `importance` | 1–5; `5` opts a global memory into every-session injection |\n| `confidence` | 0.0–1.0; reserved for janitor / promotion logic |\n| `project_scope` | NULL = global; else project_name (joined with registry) |\n| `dedup_key` | UNIQUE; prevents repeated learns of the same fact |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending` / `deprecated` / `superseded` — soft-delete + supersession |\n| `embedding` | Float32 BLOB; semantic fallback vector. Stripped from MCP responses (would balloon to ~260 KB). |\n| `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count` | Decay inputs |\n| `superseded_by`, `superseded_at` | Pointer to the memory that replaced this one (audit trail) |\n| `workspace_id`, `agent_id` | T16 multi-agent metadata; indexed |\n\n### 5.3 `context_items` — key columns\n\n| Column | Purpose |\n|--------|---------|\n| `project_name` | Foreign-keyed by name to the registry |\n| `type` | `goal` / `decision` / `progress` / `gotcha` |\n| `content` | Free text |\n| `permanent` | 1 for decision/gotcha; 0 for goal/progress |\n| `memory_id` | Optional link back to a promoted global memory |\n| `status` | `active` / `pending_promotion` / `promoted` |\n\n### 5.4 FTS5 setup\n\n- `memories_fts` is a `content='memories'` external-content FTS5 virtual table.\n  Triggers (`memories_ai`, `memories_au`, `memories_ad`) keep the index in sync on\n  insert/update/delete.\n- Recall path: parameterised `MATCH` query against `memories_fts`, joined back to\n  `memories` for category/project/importance filters and decay scoring.\n- BM25 ranking is the default; the recall engine post-multiplies by importance and\n  decay factors before returning top-N.\n\n### 5.5 Decay model (current)\n\nThe current implementation applies decay at recall time, not as a stored score.\n\n- **Inputs:** `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `importance`, `created_at`.\n- **Rule sketch:**\n  - If `importance == 5`, no decay.\n  - If memory has not been recalled in 90+ days and `importance < 3`, multiply rank\n    by a decay factor (< 1).\n  - Recently-recalled memories get a freshness boost.\n- **Reporting:** `/openltm:health` summarises memories by decay bucket\n  (`fresh` / `aging` / `stale`) and surfaces top-5 staleness candidates.\n- **OQ3** (PRD §9): the exact function (linear / exponential / recall-driven) is open\n  and intended to be tuned with real recall logs.\n\n### 5.6 Relationships\n\n```mermaid\nerDiagram\n  memories ||--o{ memory_tags : tagged\n  tags ||--o{ memory_tags : labels\n  memories ||--o{ memory_relations : \"source/target\"\n  memories ||--o| memories : superseded_by\n  memories ||--o{ context_items : promoted_from\n  memories ||--|| memories_fts : \"FTS5 mirror\"\n```\n\n### 5.7 Registry (out-of-DB)\n\n`~/.claude/projects/registry.json` holds the cwd → project_name map. It is a JSON\nfile (not a table) for cross-plugin readability and trivial inspection. Concurrent\nwrite safety is **not** guaranteed — a known weakness (§7).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Architectural Decision Records\n\nEach ADR is short and load-bearing. Format: Status, Context, Decision, Alternatives,\nConsequences. Every ADR includes at least one rejected alternative.\n\n---\n\n### ADR-001 — SQLite as the storage engine\n\n**Status:** Accepted. In production since v1.0.\n\n**Context.** The plugin needs durable, queryable, low-latency storage on the\ndeveloper's machine. It must survive Claude Code restarts, plugin upgrades, and\nmachine sleep. Median write latency target: < 50 ms p95 (PRD §8.4 R3). Median recall\n< 200 ms (G2). Zero cloud dependency by default (PRD §7 N1).\n\n**Decision.** Use SQLite (via `bun:sqlite`) in WAL mode, single file at\n`${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_DATA}/openltm.db`. FTS5 virtual table for full-text search.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Postgres / managed DB.** Rejected. Adds an installation dependency, defeats the\n  zero-cloud promise, and is overkill for single-user data volumes (~10⁴–10⁶ rows\n  realistic ceiling).\n- **Flat JSON / Markdown files (the pre-1.0 design).** Rejected. No transactional\n  semantics, no FTS, no concurrent reader safety, O(N) scan per recall. The current\n  `context-summary.md` is the vestigial fallback; it is a *projection*, not the truth.\n- **DuckDB.** Considered. Better analytical perf, but heavier binary, weaker FTS\n  story, less Bun-native tooling, and write-heavy workloads (learn + decay updates)\n  favour SQLite.\n- **LevelDB / RocksDB key-value.** Rejected. No SQL, no FTS5, would need a hand-rolled\n  index for every query path.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) One-file backup story; `cp openltm.db openltm.db.bak` is a complete export.\n- (+) FTS5 ships in SQLite — no extra dependency for full-text search.\n- (+) `bun:sqlite` is in-process; no IPC overhead per query.\n- (–) Single-writer constraint (mitigated by WAL); cross-process locking is the\n  developer's responsibility to understand.\n- (–) Schema migrations must be hand-coded and idempotent (see `src/shared-db.ts`).\n  ADR-004 and §7 weakness W3 expand on this.\n- (–) Embedding column as BLOB grows the row size fast; the formatter strips it\n  before MCP transmission to avoid 260 KB-per-memory responses.\n\n---\n\n### ADR-002 — Hook-based lifecycle integration\n\n**Status:** Accepted.\n\n**Context.** Claude Code is a black-box harness. The plugin needs to (a) inject\ncontext at session start, (b) survive compaction without state loss, (c) record\nprogress at session end, and (d) propose learnings post-session. MCP tools cover the\n\"on demand\" surface but not \"automatic on lifecycle event\".\n\n**Decision.** Use Claude Code's hook surface for four lifecycle events:\n`SessionStart`, `PreCompact`, `EvaluateSession`, `UpdateContext`. Hooks are\nshort-lived Bun scripts in `hooks/`. They share the DB connection logic with the MCP\nserver via `src/shared-db.ts`.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **MCP-only.** Rejected. There is no MCP equivalent to \"this is a fresh session,\n  inject context now\". Without hooks, the developer would have to manually call\n  `context` at every session start — defeats J1 and US-1.\n- **Background daemon.** Rejected. Long-lived process management on developer\n  machines is fragile (sleep/wake, terminal close). Also conflates \"react to event\"\n  with \"serve queries\".\n- **Polling cron.** Rejected. Not aligned with session boundaries; can't inject at\n  start.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Hook semantics align directly with PRD user stories US-1, US-4, US-13, US-17.\n- (+) Each hook is independently testable and replaceable.\n- (–) Hook failures are silent by default — drove the need for `/openltm:doctor` (US-9).\n- (–) Coupling to Claude Code's hook contract; if the harness changes the contract,\n  hooks break. Mitigated by the `update-wiring.ts` postinstall script that keeps\n  `settings.json` in sync.\n- (–) Four hook processes per session add some startup latency; offset by Bun's\n  fast cold start (~30 ms typical).\n\n---\n\n### ADR-003 — FTS5 for recall (with semantic fallback)\n\n**Status:** Accepted, with semantic fallback as a deliberate hedge.\n\n**Context.** Recall is the primary read path (PRD G2). It must return relevant\nmemories on natural-language queries in under 200 ms median. The data set is\nsingle-developer-scale (10²–10⁵ memories realistically). There is no model server.\n\n**Decision.** Primary search is SQLite FTS5 BM25 over `memories.content`. If FTS5\nreturns < 3 results for a query, fall back to a semantic similarity pass over the\n`embedding` BLOB column. Merge results, dedup by id, apply decay + importance\nboost, return top-N.\n\n**Alternatives considered.**\n\n- **Pure embeddings (vector search).** Rejected. (a) Requires an embedding provider\n  (model call or bundled runtime) — violates PRD N4. (b) Higher latency per query.\n  (c) FTS5 alone is sufficient for the bulk of \"did I learn X?\" lookups, which are\n  keyword-shaped.\n- **External vector DB (Qdrant, Chroma, sqlite-vss).** Rejected. Adds a binary\n  dependency or a sidecar process. Single-user scale doesn't justify it.\n- **Pure FTS5 (no semantic fallback).** Rejected. FTS5 is brittle for paraphrased\n  queries (\"how do we handle async errors\" vs. memory text \"promise rejection\n  patterns\"). The fallback is the cheapest hedge.\n- **Trigram / fuzzy matching only.** Rejected. Tokenisation-aware ranking (BM25)\n  beats raw similarity for natural language.\n\n**Consequences.**\n\n- (+) Zero extra dependencies; FTS5 is in SQLite already.\n- (+) Determinism — same query, same DB, same ranking.\n- (–) Embedding column adds storage cost; the BLOB is stripped from MCP responses\n  to avoid bloat.\n- (–) \"Semantic fallback\" today uses whatever embedding source is available\n  (deterministic local hash or a future tool call) — OQ1 in the PRD remains open.\n- (–) Recall ranking is not user-explainable today (G-K is the gap).\n\n---\n\n### ADR-004 — Memory decay model\n\n**Status:** Accepted (provisional). Function shape under experiment (PRD OQ3).\n\n**Context.** Without decay, recall results stagnate as the DB grows. PRD US-5 demands\nthat low-importance, never-recalled memories fade. PRD G2 demands fresh, fast recall.\n\n**Decision.** Decay is computed at **recall time**, not stored. Inputs:\n`importance`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, `created_at`. Rules:\n","lineStart":261,"lineEnd":520,"totalLines":1075,"truncated":true}},"title":"specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/OpenLtm-main/docs/03-architecture.md","time":{"start":1780925658245,"end":1780925658251}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ee615752adda4c016a26c4da330c81919b84dbc87ea9a555"}},"id":"prt_ea770f4820011Wj4RGj9ddbpng","sessionID":"ses_158903c2bffeCx3bRrBHJwKOQa","messageID":"msg_ea770c180001S6lu2NadozweRv"}}
